Nasreen baji, 30, has resided in Vehari, Pakistan with her family for the past 20 years in a two room brick house she owns. Her husband, A. M., delivers construction supplies from one place to another on a donkey cart. 
	
The mother of one son who runs a small hotel in the food market where he sells Punjabi foods such as dahi bhalas, pakodas, Nasreen baji prepares embroidered dresses. She saves her income in a committee and plans to marry off her son with the committee amount. She is applying for a loan to buy an auto-rickshaw (a local three-wheeled motor vehicle) for her husband because his donkey has died and the cart is becoming dilapidated. 

Nasreen baji is the group leader of four other women from her locality:

Shamim baji wants a loan to buy tools for her motor workshop;
Khadija baji wants a loan to buy seasonal fruits for her fruit-selling business; 
Nargis begum baji wants a loan to buy groceries for her grocery shop;
Haleema baji wants a loan to repair her auto-rickshaw (a local three-wheeled motor vehicle). 

This is a group loan. The loan funds will be distributed among the group members, each of whom will invest in her own business. The members guarantee one another's loans, so if one member does not repay, the other members are responsible.
